</h3><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-24_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Paediatric first aid is not merely a skill but a vital safeguard in homes, schools, and child care settings. Statistics show that in the UK, accidents are the leading cause of death in children over one year old, emphasising the need for effective first aid readiness. Furthermore, a research indicates that over 40% of parents have witnessed their child in a life-threatening situation, yet less than 20% felt confident to respond effectively.









</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-26_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-27_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-28_ pf-heading-1-h3">What is paediatric first aid?</h3><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-30_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Paediatric first aid refers to the immediate care given to infants and children who are injured or ill before professional medical help can be obtained. It encompasses a range of responses, from treating minor cuts and bruises to performing life-saving measures like CPR.









</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-32_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-33_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-34_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions and training requirements</h3><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-36_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">A paediatric first aider is typically required to have undergone a comprehensive training programme that covers:









</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-cbTzjv cdRhtw pf-38_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-39_ pf-text-1"><strong>Basic Life Support (BLS) for children</strong> - This includes skills like performing child CPR and managing a choking infant.












</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-41_ pf-text-1"><strong>Managing injuries and illnesses </strong>- This involves handling fractures, burns, allergic reactions, and other common childhood conditions.













</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-43_ pf-text-1"><strong>Emergency planning and risk assessment </strong>- Understanding how to create a safe environment for children and anticipate potential hazards.














</li></ul><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-45_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Training is often provided in accordance with guidelines from the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) and other relevant bodies, ensuring that first aiders are well-prepared to meet the needs of children in different age groups.










</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-47_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-48_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-49_ pf-heading-1-h3">Relevant legislation and regulations</h3><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-51_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">In the UK, the provision of paediatric first aid is supported by various pieces of legislation and regulatory guidance:










</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-cbTzjv cdRhtw pf-53_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-54_ pf-text-1"><strong>The Health and Safety (First-Aid) Regulations 1981</strong> - These regulations require employers to provide adequate and appropriate equipment, facilities, and personnel to ensure employees receive immediate attention if they are injured or taken ill at work.














</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-56_ pf-text-1"><strong>Early Years Foundation Stage (EYFS) framework</strong> - It mandates that all newly qualified entrants to the early years workforce in England holding a Level 2 and/or Level 3 qualification must have either a full paediatric first aid (PFA) or an emergency PFA certificate before they can be included in the required staff: child ratios.














</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-58_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-59_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-60_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices in paediatric first aid</h3><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-62_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Best practices in paediatric first aid include regular training updates, ensuring first aid kits are tailored to children, and maintaining a clear understanding of legal responsibilities in child care settings. Continuous assessment of potential risks in environments frequented by children is also considered best practice.









</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-64_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-65_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-66_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recommendations for effective paediatric first aid</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-cbTzjv cdRhtw pf-68_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-69_ pf-text-1"><strong>Regular training</strong> - Refresh skills biennially to keep up with the latest guidelines and techniques.











</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-71_ pf-text-1"><strong>Customised first aid kits</strong> - Equip kits with items specifically needed for treating children.













</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-73_ pf-text-1"><strong>Risk assessment </strong>- Conduct regular checks in environments where children are present to identify and mitigate potential hazards.















